            + THe Great Turkish War was a series of conflicts between the Ottoman Empire and 
                \b the Holy League consisting of the Holy Roman Empire, Poland-Lithuania, Venice, Russia, and Habsburg Hungary. 
                \b Intensive fighting began in 1683 and ended with the signing of the Treaty of Karlowitz in 1699. 
                \b The war was a defeat for the Ottoman Empire, which for the first time lost large amounts of territory, 
                \b in Hungary and the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth, as well as part of the western Balkans. 
                \b The war was significant also by being the first time that Russia was involved in an alliance with Western Europe.
            + The French did not join the Holy League, 
                \b as they had agreed to reviving an informal Franco-Ottoman alliance in 1673, 
                \b in exchange for Louis XIV being recognized as a protector of Catholics in the Ottoman regime.
            + Initially, Louis XIV took advantage of the start of the war to extend their eastern borders in the War of the Reunions, 
                \b taking Luxembourg and Strasbourg in the Truce of Ratisbon. 
                \b However, as the Holy League made gains against the Ottoman Empire, capturing Belgrade by 1688, 
                \b the French began to worry that their Habsburg rivals will grow too powerful and eventually turn on France. 
                \b The Glorious Revolution was also a matter of concern for the French, 
                \b as William III of Orange-Nassau was being invited by English nobles in the Invitation to William letter to take control of England as king. 
                \b Therefore, the French besieged Philippsburg on 27 September 1688, 
                \b breaking the truce and triggering the separate Nine Years' War, which relieved the Turks.
