            + The War of the Austrian Succession was the last of the three major Bourbon-Habsburg wars of the first half of the 18th century. 
                \b It was preceded by the 1700–1715 War of the Spanish Succession, which confirmed Bourbon control of Spain, 
                \b but where the Spanish crown ceded control of much of its European territory to the Habsburgs, 
                \b and the 1733–1735 War of the Polish Succession,
                \b which began as an unrelated conflict, 
                \b but was primarily used as a proxy war by the Bourbons and Habsburgs and 
                \b mainly resulted in several significant territorial exchanges between the two great dynasties. 
                \b The War of the Austrian Succession was fought from 1740 to 1748, 
                \b and marked the rise of Prussia as a great power.
                \b Related conflicts included King George's War, the War of Jenkins' Ear, 
                \b the First Carnatic War and the First and the Second Silesian Wars.
            + The pretext for the war was Maria Theresa's right to inherit her father Emperor Charles VI's crowns in the Habsburg monarchy, 
                \b but France, Prussia and Bavaria saw it as an opportunity to challenge Habsburg power. 
                \b Maria Theresa was backed by Britain, the Dutch Republic and Hanover, 
                \b which were collectively known as the Pragmatic Allies. 
                \b As the conflict widened, it drew in other participants, among them Spain, Sardinia, Saxony, Sweden and Russia.
            + There were four primary theatres of the war: Central Europe, the Austrian Netherlands, Italy, and the seas. 
                \b Prussia occupied Silesia in 1740 and repulsed Austrian efforts to regain it, 
                \b and between 1745 and 1748, France conquered most of the Austrian Netherlands. 
                \b Elsewhere, Austria and Sardinia defeated Spanish attempts to regain territories in Northern Italy, and 
                \b by 1747, a British naval blockade was crippling French trade.
            + The war ended with the Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle (1748) 
                \b by which Maria Theresa was confirmed as Archduchess of Austria and Queen of Hungary. 
                \b The treaty reflected that stalemate since most of the commercial issues that had led to the war were left unresolved, 
                \b and many of the signatories were unhappy with the terms. 
                \b Although the war had nearly bankrupted the state, 
                \b Louis XV withdrew from the Low Countries for minimal benefit, 
                \b to the dismay of France's nobility and populace. 
                \b The Spanish considered their gains in Italy inadequate since they had failed to recover Menorca or Gibraltar and 
                \b viewed the reassertion of British commercial rights in the Americas as an insult.
            + Although Maria Theresa was acknowledged as her father's heir, 
                \b she did not consider that a concession and deeply resented Britain's role in forcing her to cede Silesia to Prussia. 
                \b For British statesmen, the war demonstrated the vulnerability of George II's German possession of Hanover to Prussia, 
                \b and many politicians considered they had received little benefit from the enormous subsidies paid to Austria.
            + The only state to come out unequivocally better from the war was likely Prussia and its king, Frederick the Great, 
                \b which not only emerged territorially enriched by the acquisition of the large and productive land of Silesia, 
                \b but also raised its profile to become a major great power of Europe for the next century, 
                \b serving as a northern German counterbalance to Austrians.
            + The result was the realignment known as the Diplomatic Revolution, 
                \b a major restructuring of the centuries-old alliance system in Europe. 
                \b Habsburg Austria and Bourbon France emerged as allies to counterbalance the ascendent Prussia, 
                \b which itself became allied to Great Britain, ending the Anglo-Austrian Alliance which had been in place for the first half of the century. 
                \b These shifting alliances set up the Seven Years' War in the following decade.

