                \b already facing nationwide Cuban insurgent attacks and further devastated by yellow fever.
                \b The invaders obtained the surrender of Santiago de Cuba and Manila despite the good performance of some Spanish infantry units, 
                \b and fierce fighting for positions such as San Juan Hill.
                \b Madrid sued for peace after two Spanish squadrons were sunk in the battles of Santiago de Cuba and Manila Bay, 
                \b and a third, more modern fleet was recalled home to protect the Spanish coasts.
            + The war ended with the 1898 Treaty of Paris, negotiated on terms favorable to the United States. 
                \b The treaty ceded ownership of Puerto Rico, Guam, and the Philippine islands from Spain to the United States and 
                \b granted the United States temporary control of Cuba. 
                \b The cession of the Philippines involved payment of $20 million ($650 million today) to Spain by the U.S. 
                \b to cover infrastructure owned by Spain.
            + The defeat and loss of the Spanish Empire's last remnants was a profound shock to Spain's national psyche and 
                \b provoked a thorough philosophical and artistic reevaluation of Spanish society known as the Generation of '98.
                \b The United States meanwhile not only became a major power, 
                \b but also gained several island possessions spanning the globe, 
                \b which provoked rancorous debate over the wisdom of expansionism.

    event second_boer_war_1899
        title The Second Boer War
        date
            start 1899/12/16
            end 1902/3/21
        wiki https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_Boer_War
            + The Second Boer War 1899-1902, 
                \b was a conflict fought between the British Empire and the two Boer Republics (the South African Republic and the Orange Free State) 
                \b over the Empire's influence in Southern Africa from 1899 to 1902. 
                \b Triggered by the discovery of diamond and gold deposits in the Boer republics, 
                \b the Boers launched successful attacks against British outposts in the opening stages of the war 
                \b before being pushed back by imperial reinforcements. 
                \b Though the British swiftly occupied the Boer republics, 
                \b numerous Boers refused to accept defeat and engaged in guerrilla warfare. 
                \b Eventually, British scorched earth policies brought the remaining Boer guerillas to the negotiating table, ending the war.
            + The conflict broke out in 1899 after the failure of the Bloemfontein Conference and 
                \b Boer irregulars and militia attacked colonial settlements in nearby British colonies. 
                \b Starting in October 1899, the Boers placed Ladysmith, Kimberley, and Mafeking under siege, 
                \b and won a string of victories at Colenso, Magersfontein and Stormberg. 
                \b In response to these developments, increased numbers of British Army soldiers were brought to Southern Africa, 
                \b and mounted largely unsuccessful attacks against the Boers. 
                \b However, British military fortunes changed when their commanding officer, General Redvers Buller was replaced by Lord Roberts and Lord Kitchener, 
                \b who relieved the three besieged cities and invaded the two Boer Republics in early 1900 at the head of a 180,000-strong expeditionary force. 
                \b The Boers, aware they were unable to resist such a large force, chose to refrain from fighting pitched battles, 
                \b allowing the British to occupy both republics and their capitals, Pretoria and Bloemfontein.
            + Boer politicians, including President of the South African Republic Paul Kruger either fled the region or went into hiding; 
                \b the British Empire officially annexed the two republics in 1900. 
                \b In Britain, the Conservative ministry led by Lord Salisbury attempted to capitalise on British military successes by calling an early general election, 
                \b which was dubbed by contemporary observers as a "khaki election". 
                \b However, numerous Boer fighters took to the hills and launched a guerrilla campaign against the British occupational forces, 
                \b becoming known as bittereinders. 
                \b Led by prominent generals such as Louis Botha, Jan Smuts, Christiaan de Wet, and Koos de la Rey, 
                \b Boer guerrillas launched a campaign of hit-and-run attacks and ambushes against the British, 
                \b which would continue for two years.
            + The Boer guerrilla campaign proved difficult for the British to defeat, 
                \b due in part to British unfamiliarity with guerrilla tactics 
                \b and extensive support for the guerrillas among the civilian population in the Boer Republics. 
                \b In response to continued failures to defeat the Boer guerillas, 
                \b British high command ordered several scorched earth policies to be implemented as part of a large scale and multi-pronged counterinsurgency campaign; 
                \b a complex network of nets, blockhouses, strongpoints and barbed wire fences was constructed, 
                \b virtually partitioning the occupied republics. 
                \b British troops were ordered to destroy farms and slaughter livestock to deny them to Boer guerillas, 
                \b and over a hundred thousand Boer civilians (mostly women and children) were forcibly relocated into concentration camps, 
                \b where 26,000 died of various causes, mostly starvation and disease. 
                \b Black Africans in the same areas were also interned in concentration camps as well to prevent them from supplying the Boers; 
                \b 20,000 died in the camps as well, largely due to the same causes as their Boer counterparts.
            + In addition to these scorched earth policies, British mounted infantry units were deployed to track down and engage individual Boer guerillas units; 
                \b by this stage of the war, all battles being fought were small-scale skirmishes. 
                \b Few combatants on either side were killed in action, with most casualties coming via disease. 
                \b Lord Kitchener began to offer generous terms of surrender to remaining Boer leaders in an effort to bring an end to the conflict. 
                \b Eager to ensure their fellow Boers were released from the concentration camps, 
                \b the majority of Boer commanders accepted the British terms in the Treaty of Vereeniging, 
                \b formally surrendering in May 1902. 
                \b The former republics were transformed into the British colonies of the Transvaal and Orange River, 
                \b and in 1910 were merged with the Natal and Cape Colonies to form the Union of South Africa, 
                \b a self-governing dominion within the British Empire.
            + British expeditionary efforts were aided significantly by local colonial forces from the Cape Colony, 
                \b the Natal Colony, Rhodesia, as well as volunteers from the British Isles and the British Empire worldwide, 
                \b particularly Australia, Canada, India and New Zealand. 
                \b Later in the war, Black African recruits contributed increasingly to the British war effort.
                \b International public opinion was generally sympathetic to the Boers and hostile to the British.
                \b Even within the United Kingdom, there existed significant opposition to the war. 
                \b As a result, the Boer cause attracted thousands of volunteers from neutral countries all over the world, 
                \b including German Empire, United States, Russia and even some parts of the British Empire such as Australia and Ireland.
                \b Many consider the Boer War as marking the beginning of the questioning of the British Empire's veneer of impenetrable global dominance; 
                \b this is due to the war's surprisingly long duration and the unforeseen, 
                \b discouraging losses suffered by the British fighting the "cobbled-together army" of Boers.

